\begin_layout Subsection*
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.1 Risk Management Framework (RMF) Adoption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Information Operations Department adopts the NIST Risk Management Framework (RMF) as the strategic methodology for managing system lifecycles.
 All County information systems shall move through the RMF stages:
 Prepare,
 Categorize,
 Select,
 Implement,
 Assess,
 Authorize,
 and Monitor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Risk Management Strategy
\series default
:
 The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a documented Risk Management Strategy that defines risk appetite/tolerance,
 prioritization criteria,
 management decision rules for selecting risk responses,
 scoring methodology (
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
),
 reporting thresholds,
 and review cadence;
 the IT Director shall approve it at least annually (
\series bold
NIST PM-9
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Continuous Monitoring
\series default
:
 Operational risk management shall align with the NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) 2.0 functions.
 Risk monitoring shall be integrated into the Department's Continuous Monitoring program,
 and outputs shall be recorded as evidence in the Risk Register and/or control assessment records.
 The program shall explicitly track:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Effectiveness
\series default
:
 Monitoring ensuring security controls are operating as intended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Compliance
\series default
:
 Monitoring ensuring adherence to CJIS,
 HIPAA,
 PCI,
 and County policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Change
\series default
:
 Monitoring identifying changes to systems or environments that alter the risk profile.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.2 Security Categorization (FIPS 199)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All County information systems must be categorized based on the potential impact of a loss of confidentiality,
 integrity,
 or availability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Authorizing Official Approval
\series default
:
 The IT Director (AO) shall review and formally approve the security categorization of all information systems (
\series bold
NIST RA-2
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Documentation
\series default
:
 Security categorization results and rationale shall be documented in the 
\series bold
System Security Plan (SSP)
\series default
 or equivalent system security documentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Criminal Justice Information (CJI)
\series default
:
 As a County baseline,
 all systems processing,
 storing,
 or transmitting CJI shall be categorized,
 at a minimum,
 as 
\series bold
Moderate Impact
\series default
 and shall implement CJIS-required controls and County controls commensurate with that impact level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Categorization Review
\series default
:
 Security categorizations must be reviewed annually or following any significant system change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.3 Risk Assessment Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Risk assessments must identify threats,
 vulnerabilities,
 likelihood,
 and impact specific to the system environment.
 Assessments shall utilize the standardized scoring criteria defined in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 (Risk Assessment Matrix).
 Assessments shall explicitly consider supply chain risks in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Assessment Cadence
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Quarterly Review
\series default
:
 All risk assessments shall be reviewed at least 
\series bold
Quarterly
\series default
.
 "Review" is defined as risk register reconciliation,
 status validation,
 and treatment progress confirmation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Annual Update
\series default
:
 Formal risk assessment updates (re-scoring and threat refresh) shall be performed at least 
\series bold
Annually
\series default
 for non-critical systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
CJI/Critical Update
\series default
:
 Formal risk assessment updates shall be performed at least 
\series bold
Quarterly
\series default
 for CJI and Critical Systems (
\series bold
CJIS RA-3
\series default
).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Event-Driven Reviews
\series default
:
 A risk assessment update shall be initiated within five (5) business days following any security incident,
 material system change,
 significant control failure,
 or confirmed vulnerability affecting County systems (
\series bold
NIST RA-3
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Policy Review
\series default
:
 This policy shall be reviewed at least annually in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and updated as necessary to reflect changes in the risk environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Threat Intelligence
\series default
:
 The process shall incorporate cyber threat intelligence received from external information-sharing forums (e.g.,
 MS-ISAC,
 FBI InfraGard) (
\series bold
NIST ID.RA-02
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.4 Vulnerability Monitoring and Remediation Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Department shall employ automated tools to scan for vulnerabilities in information systems and hosted applications.
 Operational patching procedures and specific tool configurations shall be maintained in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Vulnerability and Patch Management Policy).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Scope
\series default
:
 Scans shall cover internal assets,
 external perimeter assets,
 and web applications.
 Privileged vulnerability scans shall require explicit authorization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Scanning Frequency
\series default
:
 Vulnerability scans shall be performed at least Monthly (County Baseline) and whenever new vulnerabilities potentially affecting the system are identified and reported,
 including following major configuration changes and critical exploit advisories (
\series bold
CJIS RA-5
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Remediation Timelines
\series default
:
 To manage technical risk,
 the Department shall adhere to the following strict remediation timelines.
 Severity ratings shall be based on the County-approved scoring standard (e.g.,
 CVSS base score or vendor severity,
 whichever is higher),
 as defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:2.09"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and 
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Critical Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 
\series bold
15 days
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
High Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 
\series bold
30 days
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Medium Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 
\series bold
60 days
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Low Severity
\series default
:
 Remediate within 
\series bold
90 days
\series default
.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Enforcement
\series default
:
 When remediation will exceed the timelines above,
 the Administrator shall document the item in a POA&M and submit a 
\series bold
Risk Acceptance Memo
\series default
 before the remediation deadline expires.
 This memo must include 
\series bold
compensating controls
\series default
 to mitigate risk during the exposure window and a defined expiration date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.5 Risk Response Strategies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon identification of a risk,
 the Department must select one of the following response strategies (
\series bold
NIST RA-7
\series default
):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Mitigate
\series default
:
 Apply controls (patches,
 configuration changes,
 and physical barriers) to reduce risk to an acceptable level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Accept
\series default
:
 Formally acknowledge the risk.
 Risk acceptance requires written justification,
 System Owner concurrence,
 and approval by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Transfer
\series default
:
 Shift liability to a third party (e.g.,
 cyber insurance,
 managed service contracts).
 Vendor risk transfer shall be managed in accordance with 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Avoid
\series default
:
 Discontinue the activity,
 system,
 or vendor relationship causing the risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.6 Criticality Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Department shall identify critical system components and functions by performing a criticality analysis at the planning,
 design,
 and implementation stages (
\series bold
NIST RA-9
\series default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
High Value Assets (HVAs)
\series default
:
 Systems designated as "Critical" or "High Value" in the 
\series bold
Disaster Recovery Plan
\series default
 or 
\series bold
System Security Plan (SSP)
\series default
 shall be prioritized for advanced protection measures and continuity planning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.7 Risk Register and Reporting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Assistant IT Director shall maintain a centralized Risk Register tracking all identified risks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
System of Record
\series default
:
 The Risk Register shall be maintained in the Department's designated 
\series bold
System of Record
\series default
 (e.g.,
 Redmine or secured GRC platform) with strict role-based access controls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Sensitive Security Information
\series default
:
 The Risk Register and supporting evidence shall be treated as sensitive security documentation;
 access shall be restricted to authorized personnel on a need-to-know basis,
 and disclosures shall be managed in accordance with County policy and CJIS requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Minimum Data Fields
\series default
:
 The Risk Register shall contain,
 at a minimum:
 Risk ID,
 Date Identified,
 System/Asset,
 System Owner,
 CJI Indicator (Y/N),
 Risk Category,
 CVE/CVSS (if applicable),
 Inherent/Residual Score,
 Control Mapping,
 Treatment Strategy,
 POA&M Linkage,
 Status,
 Due Date,
 and Acceptance Authority.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
POA&M Updates
\series default
:
 Plans of Action and Milestones (POA&Ms) for unremediated risks shall be updated at least every 
\series bold
six (6) months
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Risk-Based Frequency
\series default
:
 For CJI systems,
 Critical systems,
 and any risk rated "High" or "Critical," POA&Ms shall be reviewed and updated at least 
\series bold
Quarterly
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Reporting
\series default
:
 A summary of the County’s risk posture,
 including all accepted "High" risks,
 shall be reported to the County Manager annually by the IT Director.
\end_layout

